com.pyramidacceptors.ptalk.api.event

Enum Events

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<Events>
      • com.pyramidacceptors.ptalk.api.event.Events
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<Events>

    public enum Events
extends java.lang.Enum<Events>
    The bill acceptor will pass through a series of "States" during bill processing. The acceptor will always be in a " State." If the acceptor is waiting for a bill insertion, it will report an "Idle" state to the master. If the acceptor is reading a bill , i t will b e reporting an "Accepting" state to the master. Only one state can be set at a time. The acceptor m a y also have a reported "Event" taking place. For example, if the acceptor has just stacked a bill in the "Stacking Mechanism", it will report a "Stacked" event and since it is now waiting for another bill insertion, it will also report an "Idle" state within the same message. It is possible for a multiple event to be set in a message. Events are temporary. For example, when a message sent by the acceptor has been received by the master and a new message is then sent by the master, with a new MSG/ack number, the acceptor should clear the previous event bit that is set when it sends its next response.
    Since:
    1.0.0.0

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • Idling

        public static final Events Idling
        The bill acceptor has not processed a bill and is waiting for a bill to be inserted. There are no problems with the acceptor is this state.

      • Accepting

        public static final Events Accepting
        In this state, a bill is being received through the acceptor. The bill has not reached the "Escrow" position yet.

      • Escrowed

        public static final Events Escrowed
        The bill is valid and in sitting inside the bill acceptor. The "Escrow State" reports the bill value field and will indicate the denomination of the bill. If the bill is invalid, the state of escrow would never be reported. When the acceptor first powers up and a bill is found to be in escrow, the acceptor would report in an escrow state with the "Bill Value Field" set to 000 (unknown value). The master would then send a return message to the acceptor. The acceptor finishes with a returned event, then it goes back to the idle state.

      • Stacking

        public static final Events Stacking
        The acceptor remains in this state as it transports the bill from the escrow position toward a secure position past all the bill acceptors internal sensors, as well as the stacking mechanism sensors. The acceptor will not change states until the bill is stacked or jammed. During power up if a bill is not in the escrow position, this state bit and the power up bit will be reported.

      • Stacked

        public static final Events Stacked
        After the bill has been successfully stacked into the cashbox, this event is reported. The master will then issues the credit for the bill.

      • Returning

        public static final Events Returning
        This state is set for the purpose of returning a bill to the patron. The master orders the bill to be returned because it responded to an Escrowed message and did not want to accept this bill. A "Returning" message and a "Rejected" message are quite different. A returning message means that the master did not want the acceptor to take a particular bill of valid currency. A rejected message is sent because the acceptor found the bill to be not valid.

      • Returned

        public static final Events Returned
        When the master tells the slave to return a bill (After an Escrowed message), this message is sent after the bill has been successfully returned to the patron. This bill was valid but for some reason, the master wanted it to be returned.

      • Cheated

        public static final Events Cheated
        If the acceptor perceives a bill as being manipulated, this event reports it. The bill may be returned to the patron, or be stacked with no credit issued. (Bill Value Field = 000)

      • BillRejected

        public static final Events BillRejected
        A bill will be returned to the patron because the acceptor found it to be invalid.

      • BillJammed

        public static final Events BillJammed
        The acceptor can not stack a bill or return the bill due to an error. The acceptor will keep sending this message until it has stopped trying to complete the operation (stack or return). If the jammed bill is removed, the acceptor will automatically exit this state.

      • StackerFull

        public static final Events StackerFull
        If this state has been reported, the acceptor can no longer accept any bills. Usually, this indicates that the cashbox is full.

      • BillCasetteRemoved

        public static final Events BillCasetteRemoved
        (controlled by the bill acceptor) When the cassette is present, this bit will be set to a logic high. If there is no cassette, the bit will be cleared. Therefore, the acceptor will not accept any bills. Note: not used on

      • PowerUp

        public static final Events PowerUp
        The unit is just powering up and is not ready to accept bills.

      • InvalidCommand

        public static final Events InvalidCommand
        An invalid command or message was sent by the slave.

      • Failure

        public static final Events Failure
        If this state has been reported, the acceptor is implying that a condition exists that prevents the bill acceptor from accepting any more currency. For example, a sensor may have failed, then the acceptor will enter this state.

      • Credit

        public static final Events Credit
        A valid credit message has been received.

      • SerialData

        public static final Events SerialData
        Raised whenever serial data is sent or received

      • CommunicationFailure

        public static final Events CommunicationFailure
        Serial communication is broken. Either the transmission is failing because the port is no longer available, reading is failing because the acceptor is disconnected, or USB serial converter driver completely and utterly failed.

      • Generic

        public static final Events Generic
        Fall back event in the event that we know something happened but we're not quite sure what.
